{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9e4c08f5-0af3-4647-9370-9a2b4657b2b3","content":"Since you already have the dump file collected, the next step is **analyzing** it. Here are the recommended tools:\n\n### On Linux/macOS/Windows (cross-platform)\n```bash\n# Install the tool if needed\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n\n# Start interactive analysis\ndotnet-dump analyze <your-file.dmp>\n```\n\nKey commands inside the analyzer:\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `clrstack` | Managed call stack of current thread |\n| `pe` (PrintException) | Show last exception details |\n| `dumpheap -stat` | Heap summary (for OOM crashes) |\n| `threads` | List all managed threads |\n| `setthread <id>` | Switch thread, then `clrstack` |\n| `dso` | Dump stack objects |\n\n### On Windows (richer experience)\n- **Visual Studio** → File → Open → open the `.dmp` file → \"Debug with Managed Only\"\n- **WinDbg** with SOS: `!analyze -v`, `!clrstack`, `!pe`\n\n### Typical workflow\n1. Run `pe` to check if there's an unhandled exception\n2. Run `threads` to find the faulting thread\n3. Run `setthread <id>` + `clrstack` to see its call stack\n4. Use `dso` to inspect objects on the stack\n\nWould you like me to install `dotnet-dump` on this machine so we can analyze your dump file together? If so, please share the path to your `.dmp` file.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"837a22f0-f5a9-419a-a6a5-693b1a42eaff","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has a .dmp crash dump file from a .NET application and wants to analyze it to find the root cause of the crash. Let me help them with this.\n\nLooking at the available skills, I see there's a `dump-collect` skill, but its description says it's for **configuring and collecting** crash dumps, and explicitly states \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze\". So that skill is not appropriate here.\n\nThere's also `dotnet-trace-collect` which is for capturing diagnostic artifacts, not analyzing dumps.\n\nThe other skills (android-tombstone-symbolication, apple-crash-symbolication) are for symbolication of specific crash log formats, not .dmp analysis.\n\n\nNone of the available skills directly support analyzing .dmp files, so I'll guide you through the process manually. For .NET crash dumps, `dotnet-dump analyze` is the most practical cross-platform tool, though WinDbg with SOS and lldb with SOS are also options depending on your platform. Let me check if dotnet-dump is available and walk you through how to use it.","outputTokens":687,"requestId":"9809:386D1F:5889E9F:611C888:69F407FD"},"id":"190018a0-b9f4-4916-bebe-1850282d75ac","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:55:27.828Z","parentId":"12b2f92e-22db-49f2-a974-872d6c086ae1"}
